**To Reproduce**
1. Receive a message from a topic using ServiceBusReceiverClient.
2. Then process the received message. Suppose, it takes a very long time, e.g. 2-3 hours.
3. During the processing time, keep renewing the message lock. Please note that the server message lock time for the topic is maximum 5 minutes. And we are renewing the lock every one minute making sure that it never loses the lock.
4. Once the processing is over, send a new message to the same topic using ServiceBusSenderClient.
5. Exception comes: Cannot send a message when request response channel is disposed

**Expected behavior**

Message should have been sent to topic by using ServiceBusSenderClient without any exception. Even if there is some diconnect between sender and server, SDK should revive the connection automatically. Please note that this error is an intermittent error.

**Setup (please complete the following information):**
 - OS: UNIX
 - IDE: IntelliJ
 - Library/Libraries: com.azure:azure-messaging-servicebus:7.5.1
 - Java version: 8
 - App Server/Environment: Tomcat
 - Frameworks: Spring

**Additional context**
1. Error comes while sending a message after a long processing time.
2. Please note that this error is an intermittent error.
3. Earlier this error was very frequent in our UAT environment. Then as per the suggestion from Microsoft support, we upgraded to the latest SDK azure-messaging-servicebus v7.5.1 and it was fixed for us in UAT environment.
4. **To Reproduce**
1. Receive a message from a topic using ServiceBusReceiverClient.
2. Then process the received message. Suppose, it takes a very long time, e.g. 2-3 hours.
3. During the processing time, keep renewing the message lock. Please note that the server message lock time for the topic is maximum 5 minutes. And we are renewing the lock every one minute making sure that it never loses the lock.
4. Once the processing is over, send a new message to the same topic using ServiceBusSenderClient.
5. Exception comes: Cannot send a message when request response channel is disposed

**Expected behavior**

Message should have been sent to topic by using ServiceBusSenderClient without any exception. Even if there is some diconnect between sender and server, SDK should revive the connection automatically. Please note that this error is an intermittent error.

**Setup (please complete the following information):**
 - OS: UNIX
 - IDE: IntelliJ
 - Library/Libraries: com.azure:azure-messaging-servicebus:7.5.1
 - Java version: 8
 - App Server/Environment: Tomcat
 - Frameworks: Spring

**Additional context**
1. Error comes while sending a message after a long processing time.
2. Please note that this error is an intermittent error.
3. Earlier this error was very frequent in our UAT environment. Then as per the suggestion from Microsoft support, we upgraded to the latest SDK azure-messaging-servicebus v7.5.1 and it was fixed for us in UAT environment.
4. '2022-04-18T19:30:29Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-18T19:30:29Z', 'author_association': 'NONE', 'body': '@simonbasle - I wasn't sure if I should open a ticket or clarify here on java-doc, please let me know if ticket is better.

So this pr (607) improved the documentation of the merge operator, and I see the below doc-content, which confused me a little -  

_When dealing with an infinite source that doesn't already publish on a dedicated Scheduler, you must **isolate that source in its OWN Scheduler**, as merge would otherwise attempt to drain it before subscribing to another source_

Does this mean I should create separate "dedicated" instances of "Scheduler" object per `publishOn` operator (that is applied for each infinite-source)?

Or is it sufficient to share one instance of "Scheduler" among all `publishOn` operator (that is applied for each infinite-source), but when I instantiate that shared `Scheduler` object (say BoundedElastic), I create it with threadCap >= max-concurrency of merge operator?

(As I look at the implementation of `publishOn` operator, it seems to acquire a `Worker` at the time of subscription and hold on to it until `PublishOnSubscriber` is disposed. The merge operator indirectly ensures there is at most max-concurrency `publishOn` call, which means if Scheduler.threadCap >= max-concurrency, then each `publishOn` gets a dedicated Worker? I'm not sure my understanding is entirely correct, but this is why I asked the above question on using a shared Scheduler.)', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/reactor/reactor-core/issues/comments/1101692756/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

into the [setFuture](https://github.com/reactor/reactor-core/blob/main/reactor-core/src/main/java/reactor/core/scheduler/WorkerTask.java#L120-L127) method of WorkerTask, which won't interrupt the worker if disposition happens via sync-route.
IIUC, this means - the thread_1 running setFuture uses the marker ASYNC|SYNC_CANCELLED to check if disposition was requested by the same thread, thread_2, running call() / run().

The [setFuture](https://github.com/reactor/reactor-core/blob/e7666cc41a1a33e31366dd6dd36ea681b0ed0ced/reactor-core/src/main/java/reactor/core/scheduler/SchedulerTask.java#L102) method of SchedulerTask seems to have somewhat similar logic, but, it only checks if BOTH setFuture() and call() / run() are executed by the SAME thread to decide whether to interrupt or not. 

Just want to confirm if this difference in logic is by design or a bug.

The _global_ "BoundedElasticScheduler::schedulePeriodically" API guarantees that the task (health check here) will not execute concurrently.

The "BoundedElasticScheduler::schedulePeriodically" delegates the task execution to JDK's "ScheduledExecutorService::scheduleAtFixedRate" and it's [java-doc](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/ScheduledExecutorService.html#scheduleAtFixedRate(java.lang.Runnable,%20long,%20long,%20java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit)) says: 

> If any execution of this task takes longer than its period, then subsequent executions may start late but will not concurrently execute.

[setFuture](https://github.com/reactor/reactor-core/blob/main/reactor-core/src/main/java/reactor/core/scheduler/WorkerTask.java#L120-L127) method of WorkerTask, which won't interrupt the worker if disposition happens via sync-route.
IIUC, this means - the thread_1 running setFuture uses the marker ASYNC|SYNC_CANCELLED to check if disposition was requested by the same thread, thread_2, running call() / run().

The [setFuture](https://github.com/reactor/reactor-core/blob/e7666cc41a1a33e31366dd6dd36ea681b0ed0ced/reactor-core/src/main/java/reactor/core/scheduler/SchedulerTask.java#L102) method of SchedulerTask seems to have somewhat similar logic, but, it only checks if BOTH setFuture() and call() / run() are executed by the SAME thread to decide whether to interrupt or not. 

Just want to confirm if this difference in logic is by design or a bug.

Hi @ki1729  - @srnagar  and I had an offline chat. Srikanta explained the original reason to use "newSingleThreadScheduledExecutor" (STSE). STSE exposes the API "scheduleWithFixedDelay", which ensures the previous execution terminates before the executing the next. This way, there won't be any overlap in health checks.

We agree that STSE will create and keep the thread in the pool, even
if the thread is idle (unless allowCoreThreadTimeOut is set to true, which is false by default), so what Cx observed seems correct i.e. num_threads == num_sb_processor

The good thing is the _global_ boundedElasitcScheduler also exposes "scheduleWithFixedDelay", so we could use it instead of the current "schedulePeriodically". This way we won't end up with too many threads (due to _global_ object) and no overlap in health check.', 'created_at': '2022-04-13T19:22:55Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-13T19:22:55Z', 'html_url': Hi @ki1729  - @srnagar  and I had an offline chat. Srikanta explained the original reason to use "newSingleThreadScheduledExecutor" (STSE). STSE exposes the API "scheduleWithFixedDelay", which ensures the previous execution terminates before the executing the next. This way, there won't be any overlap in health checks.

We agree that STSE will create and keep the thread in the pool, even
if the thread is idle (unless allowCoreThreadTimeOut is set to true, which is false by default), so what Cx observed seems correct i.e. num_threads == num_sb_processor

The good thing is the _global_ boundedElasitcScheduler also exposes "scheduleWithFixedDelay", so we could use it instead of the current "schedulePeriodically". This way we won't end up with too many threads (due to _global_ object) and no overlap in health check.', 'created_at': '2022-04-13T19:22:55Z', 'updated_at': '2022-04-13T19:22:55Z', 'html_url': Sharing some thoughts.

When it comes to BoundedElastic (BE) Scheduler, setting the value "num_cpu * 4" as max_cap won't "eagerly" create and hold that many threads forever. 
1. BEScheduler tracks the idle-thread-set and busy-thread-set separately.
2. Any thread in idle thread-set, staying idle for a minute, freed and returned to the OS. 

Currently, with multiple processors each with default BEScheduler configuration, there is at least 4 category of use case -

1. If incoming traffic to all processors is HIGH and ~EQUAL [all BESchedulers are ~equally high loaded]
2. If incoming traffic to all processors is LOW and ~EQUAL [all BESchedulers are ~equally less loaded]
3. If incoming traffic to m processors is HIGH and n-m is LOW [the BESchedulers in the LOW category less busy, leaving CPU cycles for threads in BESchedulers in the HIGH category]
4. If incoming traffic changes such that a subset of processors moves from HIGH to LOW and another subset from LOW to HIGH [then the threads in set1 eventually idle-timeout+return to OS, making space for set2]

Another point applicable for all the above 4 categories is - the application is highly likely to do some IO operations (writing to DB, Disk, making network calls after processing (batch of) event) that OS utilizes to slice OS-threads among threads in BESchedulers. OS can nicely map runnable java-threads to os-threads.

So we might want users to prove with the representation of "actual data" for "real use cases" that exposing such APIs really benefits throughput and resource utilization over the (default) heuristics of BESchedulers and OS-scheduling.

Also, there are more parameters depending on the underlying Scheduler impl. Currently, none of those are leaked with the default setup. If we open up APIs, we may consider impact from that aspect.

_In the near future, once Project Loom-based v-threads are available, much of the overhead involved with the current java-thread should go away. If these parameters don't provide much value today, they likely not add much value with v-threads anyway._

'updated_at': '2022-04-12T03:42:08Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '## Root causing Cx deployed An application using SB session to 10 pods. A heap dump was taken after six days of execution, and showing excessive allocation of "reactor.core.publisher.NextProcessor$NextInner" type Out of 1,065,540, the 1,065,504 "NextInner" instances retains "MonoCacheTime+MonoCacheTime$CoordinatedSubscriber" instances, those also appeared on the top of the above histogram. Such ~1M instances of these types are leaking symptoms. These 1,065,504 "NextInner" objects are retained by one "reactor.core.publisher.NextProcessor" object. that "NextProcessor" is retained by the private variable `shutdownSignal` (type=Sink.One) in ReactorConnection. While there are multiple places library subscribe to this, the only place that exposes it via the intermediate `MonoCacheTime` operator (as appears in the second figure) is ReactorConnection::getShutdownSingal() [method](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorConnection.java#L186-L189) ```java private final Sinks.One shutdownSignalSink = Sinks.one(); @Override public Flux getShutdownSignals() { return shutdownSignalSink.asMono().cache().flux(); } ``` Scanning the source code for reference to this method, the only place it gets referenced and subscribed is in ReactorReceiver [Ctr](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorReceiver.java#L178-L181) ```java amqpConnection.getShutdownSignals().flatMap(signal -> { logger.verbose("Shutdown signal received."); return closeAsync("Connection shutdown.", null); }).subscribe()); ``` But the subscription is DISPOSED in the ReactorReceiver close [api](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/2b882d649ea8e1ef6969751589194a96315eb32f/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorReceiver.java#L345). Had it a bug in not closing ReactorReceiver, there would be ~1M instances of ReactorReceiver, but actually, there are only 250 of them. It proves that ReactorReceivers are not getting leaked and are disposed correctly. It leads us to check the implementation of Sink.One and identified a problem in Sink.One where it continues to retain the subscriber even after the disposition. A git-ticket is opened in reactor-core repro "Memory leak in SinkOneMulticast" https://github.com/reactor/reactor-core/issues/3001, and the fix coming in reactor-core-3.4.17 ## Observation_1 (Cx action item) You might have noticed that the reactor git-ticket mention about the type `SinkOneMulticast`, but in heap-dump, it's a different type `NextProcessor`. The reason for that is - Cx application seems to have one or more dependency that brings in a relatively old version of the reactor-core library (~7 months behind). The Azure ServiceBus SDK is defined to use the recent version of reactor-core-3.4.14. Back in Sept 2021, the use of `NextProcessor` in Sink.One was replaced with `SinkOneMulticast`; in this [commit](https://github.com/reactor/reactor-core/commit/472b1698ee29c9fcf5f3a23fc044f9b9b01e5679#diff-6250051e63f4ea53566d3a0ce7fa02c5d752fe5e0e1eb54c5668790c28738113) Cx needs to analyze the dependencies and align the versions of shared libraries (e.g., reactor-core, reactor-netty, etc..) by upgrading dependencies so that the application is ready to pick when reactor-core-3.4.17 is available. ## Observation_2 (Cx action item) The 1,065,504 instances of "NextProcessor$NextInner" means, over the period of 6 days, around ~1M ReactorReceiver objects were created and closed. It means ~125 ReactorReceiver instances created-disposed per minute. The only reason for such a massive churn of these objects is - that the consuming application is trying to acquire too many sessions from the service, but the producer application does not create enough sessions. Due to this, SB service DETACHes those unnecessary receivers after a 1 minute timeout. This indicates that maxConcurrentSession in the consumer application is too large. The Cx should tune this configuration according to the expected load. ## Observation_3: (Sdk action-item) The getShutdownSignals() API uses `cache()` operator. We don't have to use the cache operator here, Sink.One is capable of remembering the last signal and replaying it. While `cache()` doesn't directly contribute to any leak, we could remove it and save allocations. And the azure-core should upgrade to reactor-core 3.4.17 once released.', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/28235/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'timeline_url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/28235/timeline', 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "Hello, I was looking into the [setFuture](https://github.com/reactor/reactor-core/blob/main/reactor-core/src/main/java/reactor/core/scheduler/WorkerTask.java#L120-L127) method of WorkerTask, which won't interrupt the worker if disposition happens via sync-route.
IIUC, this means - the thread_1 running setFuture uses the marker ASYNC|SYNC_CANCELLED to check if disposition was requested by the same thread, thread_2, running call() / run().

The [setFuture](https://github.com/reactor/reactor-core/blob/e7666cc41a1a33e31366dd6dd36ea681b0ed0ced/reactor-core/src/main/java/reactor/core/scheduler/SchedulerTask.java#L102) method of SchedulerTask seems to have somewhat similar logic, but, it only checks if BOTH setFuture() and call() / run() are executed by the SAME thread to decide whether to interrupt or not. 

Just want to confirm if this difference in logic is by design or a bug.

- Fixes https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582

- Add docs to illustrate the closing flow of `RequestResponseChannel`

0, 'created_at': '2022-03-16T22:26:09Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-31T17:00:52Z', 'closed_at': '2022-03-31T17:00:52Z', 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '## Background

Two customer tickets reported that the ProtonJ error "no current delivery" appeared in the logs, but when it happened in the lower layer, it activated a code path in the upper layer that triggered a reliability issue;[ this-pr](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/24141) addressed it.

This ticket is created so that we can focus on ProtonJ error "no current delivery" .

## Root causing

As part of [this](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/27482) investigation, we learned that it is possible that the ProtonJ object state can be mutated (e.g disposed) after the "scheduling" of work to the message-pump but before the actual "execution" of the work. 

Sketching the control flow, it looks like the reason for "no current delivery"  is such a mutation; the flow appears to be below -


1. ProtonJ Receiver received a delivery. It updated its __current_ pointer to refer to this delivery then handed it over to ReceiveLinkHandler.
2. ReceiveLinkHandler [enqueues](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/0ddca1176c70abd30ab69d71c219f487aef4d0d3/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/handler/ReceiveLinkHandler.java#L164) the delivery to deliveries-Flux. 
3. The async-chain attached to deliveries-Flux [emits](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/0ddca1176c70abd30ab69d71c219f487aef4d0d3/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorReceiver.java#L82) the delivery to ReactorReceiver. 
4. The ReactorReceiver "[schedule](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/0ddca1176c70abd30ab69d71c219f487aef4d0d3/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorReceiver.java#L85)" a work to message-pump thread to decode this delivery.
5. The async-chain is waiting asynchronously for the Sink to complete. The completion happens only when scheduled work in 4 "executes" in the future.
6. The service traffic closed the amqp-receive-link, inturn [frees](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/0ddca1176c70abd30ab69d71c219f487aef4d0d3/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorReceiver.java#L347) the ProtonJ Receiver using message-pump thread. Note: the user-work in 4 and proton-j work in 6 does not execute strictly in FIFO order (two different pipes drive it), but the serial execution is guaranteed.
7. As part of freeing the ProtonJ Receiver, the ProtonJ library frees the delivery (that 4 refers to), settling the delivery and advancing the __current_ pointer. The __current_ become null.
8. ReceiveLinkHandler [enqueues](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/0ddca1176c70abd30ab69d71c219f487aef4d0d3/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/handler/ReceiveLinkHandler.java#L237) completion-event to deliveries-Flux. The completion-event emission to the async-chain is deferred because the Sink for the last event (5) is yet to be complete.
9. Work scheduled in 4 executes, but since __current_ is null and not the one the work is referring to, ProtonJ throws "no current delivery"

The exception in 9 goes to global error handling as an unhandled exception. Three 3 issues -

a. The Sink in 5 never errored
b. The completion-event in 8 never emits (because enqueued after a)
c. The unhandled exception forces the parent amqp-connection to close  

The good thing is, there is no one [downstream](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/0ddca1176c70abd30ab69d71c219f487aef4d0d3/sdk/eventhubs/azure-messaging-eventhubs/src/main/java/com/azure/messaging/eventhubs/implementation/AmqpReceiveLinkProcessor.java#L286) waiting to react to the "terminal event" from a (or b) to happen. But c is concerning because the closure of one amqp-receiver-link combined with the race resulted in amqp-connection to close, which means it causes all other healthy amqp-receiver-links in the same amqp-connection to disconnect from service. 

## Fix

Again fix is simple as [this](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/27482) ticket, i.e. do a deferred check for disposal of the Receiver so that the side effect is limited to that specific Receiver and not bypassed to the parent connection.


## References

'2022-03-30T21:09:23Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '# Summary

When creating one of the Event Hubs client types, it can be useful for a host application to be able to uniquely identify the client instance.  The Event Hubs service also supports setting the identifier of an AMQP link, which it will associate with some error messages to make it easier to correlate errors with a given client instance.  

The event processor types currently support an informational Identifier, passed in via their respective options at creation time.  The remaining Event Hubs clients should be extended to follow this pattern.

# Scope of Work

- The options for each Event Hubs client type should be extended with a string-based `Identifier` property, defaulting to `null` if not supplied by callers.

- The  Event Hubs client types should be extended with an `Identifier` property, mapping to the `Identifer` received as part of their client options.   If the options do not specify an identifier, a unique one should be generated.

- When opening an AMQP link for receiving, the identifier should be added to a link property named `com.microsoft:receiver-name` so that it can be used by the service with error messages.   _([example](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/sdk/eventhub/Azure.Messaging.EventHubs/src/Amqp/AmqpConnectionScope.cs#L672))_

- When opening an AMQP link for receiving, the identifier should be used as the `Target` in the link settings if doing so us supported by the transport.  _([example](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/sdk/eventhub/Azure.Messaging.EventHubs/src/Amqp/AmqpConnectionScope.cs#L661))_

- When opening an AMQP link for sending, the identifier should be used as the `Source` in the link settings if doing so is supported by the transport.  _([example](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/blob/main/sdk/eventhub/Azure.Messaging.EventHubs/src/Amqp/AmqpConnectionScope.cs#L771))_

- There should be no change to the logic when opening an AMQP `RequestResponse` link for management purposes; the identifier is not supported in this context.

# Success Criteria

- The API changes have been informally reviewed by the language architects and approved.

- The client options identified in the scope have been enhanced to include an `Identifier` property.

- The client types identifier in the scope have been enhanced to accept the identifier from the options, expose it via an `Identifier` property, and make use of it when creating links.

- The tests necessary for ensuring the feature works as intended have been created or adjusted and pass reliably.

- Existing tests continue to produce deterministic results and pass reliably.', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/22981/reactions', 'total_count': 2, - Fixes https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582

**Changes**

- Add `takeUtilOther()` to stop emitting `RequestResponseChannel` downstream when connection is shutdown
- Remove duplicate closing of `RequestResponseChannel` in `ReactorConnection`
- Add docs to illustrate the closing flow of `RequestResponseChannel`

One case that I think 2 uniquely cover is -


1. thread1 calls conn.getClaimsBasedSecurityNode 
2. Before 1 complete the initialization of cbsChannelProcessor, the connection.closeAsync got called from a thread2.
3. Since cbsChannelProcessor was not completely initialized, connection.closeAsync won't be able to call RRChannel.closeAsync from thread1.
4. The conn.getClaimsBasedSecurityNode completes the initialization.
5. Since the connection set shutdownsignal before its closure, the RRChannel will be able to react to it and do self-cleanup.

So although the two closure route are defined & may overlap, they seem to cover unique cases in the graph. So we might have to take a step back and think, is it ok to have those 3 or 4 lines of extra logging if that guarantees reliability JM2C.

- Fixes https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582

- Remove duplicate closing of `RequestResponseChannel` in `ReactorConnection`
- Add docs to illustrate the closing flow of `RequestResponseChannel`

'body': '# Description

- Fixes https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582 
  
See [root cause analysis](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582#issuecomment-1056389777)

**Changes**

- Add `takeUtilOther()` to stop emitting `RequestResponseChannel` downstream when connection is shutdown
- Remove duplicate closing of `RequestResponseChannel` in `ReactorConnection`
- Add docs to illustrate the closing flow of `RequestResponseChannel`

# All SDK Contribution checklist:

- [x] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. This means that previously merged commits do not appear in the history of the PR. 'body': '# Description

- Fixes https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582 
  
See [root cause analysis](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582#issuecomment-1056389777)

**Changes**

- Add `takeUtilOther()` to stop emitting `RequestResponseChannel` downstream when connection is shutdown
- Remove duplicate closing of `RequestResponseChannel` in `ReactorConnection`
- Add docs to illustrate the closing flow of `RequestResponseChannel`

# All SDK Contribution checklist:
- [x] **The pull request does not introduce [breaking changes]**
- [x] **CHANGELOG is updated for new features, bug fixes or other significant changes.**
- [x] **I have read the [contribution guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).**

- [x] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. This means that previously merged commits do not appear in the history of the PR. 'body': '# Description

- Fixes https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582 
  
See [root cause analysis](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582#issuecomment-1056389777)

**Changes**

- Add `takeUtilOther()` to stop emitting `RequestResponseChannel` downstream when connection is shutdown
- Remove duplicate closing of `RequestResponseChannel` in `ReactorConnection`
- Add docs to illustrate the closing flow of `RequestResponseChannel`

# All SDK Contribution checklist:
- [x] **The pull request does not introduce [breaking changes]**
- [x] **CHANGELOG is updated for new features, bug fixes or other significant changes.**
- [x] **I have read the [contribution guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md).**

- [x] There are a small number of commits, each of which have an informative message. This means that previously merged commits do not appear in the history of the PR. ### [Testing Guidelines](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#building-and-unit-testing)

'body': '# Description

- Fixes https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582 
  
See [root cause analysis](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582#issuecomment-1056389777)

**Changes**

- Add `takeUtilOther()` to stop emitting `RequestResponseChannel` downstream when connection is shutdown
- Remove duplicate closing of `RequestResponseChannel` in `ReactorConnection`
- Add docs to illustrate the closing flow of `RequestResponseChannel`

Regarding 1 - my understanding of the code flow is - 


1. The RRChannel first "initiates" the closure of [links](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/main/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L261-L262) which sends Detach frame to service.
2. Service responds with Detach frame acknowledging the 1, which is "happy-path finalization".
3. Because we may never get a Detach response from the service, the RRChannel [associates](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/a2c852f6c8f6eed6034342f008093d9fb6bddc68/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L270) "timeout-path finalization" to step2.
4. Either of the "finalization" (happy-path, timeout-path) is guaranteed to be executed so that the "cleanup" phase runs.
5. The "cleanup" phase is where we complete the pending Monos with error. Which is important for callers who are asynchronously blocking on sendWithAck to resume; otherwise it can result in unrecovered receivers.

The step-2 happens in response to Reactor-thread reacting to the "Read-event raised by the NW SocketChannel". 

IIRC that's the closure flow of RRChannel type (if we treat it as an independent component).

The Connection type has an internal `closeConnectionWork`, which schedules the closing of the connection, and it runs when Reactor-thread reacts to the "Read-event raised by the dispatcher Pipe", this can also indirectly "finalize" the links (RRChannel links are one of them). But `closeConnectionWork` asynchronously waits for 2 or 3 to happen as it is an operation later in the chain

So I'm not sure about the chances real deadlock, maybe missed something, but point is, it is very important RRChannel close to happen, as we have seen this being a culprit in couple of incidents.

'body': '# Description

- Fixes https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582 
  
See [root cause analysis](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582#issuecomment-1056389777)

**Changes**

- Add `takeUtilOther()` to stop emitting `RequestResponseChannel` downstream when connection is shutdown
- Remove duplicate closing of `RequestResponseChannel` in `ReactorConnection`
- Add docs to illustrate the closing flow of `RequestResponseChannel`

'body': '# Description

- Fixes https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582 
  
See [root cause analysis](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24582#issuecomment-1056389777)

**Changes**

- Add `takeUtilOther()` to stop emitting `RequestResponseChannel` downstream when connection is shutdown
- Remove duplicate closing of `RequestResponseChannel` in `ReactorConnection`
- Add docs to illustrate the closing flow of `RequestResponseChannel`

# All SDK Contribution checklist:

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/kasobol-msft/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "This PR has a prototype of a lightweight `HttpClient` based on `Netty` .
This prototype aims to build an http client that works for various types of payloads and context (sync vs async) and mostly serve sunny day scenarios while introducing all the required complexities to do so.
There's a lot of corner (mostly error) cases that remain uncovered here, but they likely won't affect existing complexity much.

Implemented features:
- Reactor-less sync execution. Sync-over-async on the `CompletableFeature` instead.
- Connection Pooling
- Buffered requests handling
- Stream-able requests handling
- On demand response buffering
- Piped based response streaming for sync calls
- Sink based response streaming for async calls (there's still plenty room for improvement here around better backpressure handling).

The client seems to be functional, i.e. `SimpleNettyHttpClientHttpClientTests extends HttpClientTests` and `SimpleNettyHttpClientRestProxyTests extends RestProxyTests` are passing.", 'created_at': 'body': '# Description

- Fixes issue #27578  

**Changes**
- Correct check condition inside `queueWork()`. If `currentWork` is not terminated, the new coming work should be place into `workQueue`.
- When REQUESTED == 0L (`CurrentWork` is completed), update `CurrentWork` to request new message.

**Detailed logic**

Below diagram shows when call receiver client to receive message:

![sync-receiver-logic](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/97088315/158547889-042cedbc-73b2-43fd-98dd-8dd26589e5c6.png) 

Below diagram shows what if current work is completed or timeout:

![work-complete-and-timeout](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/97088315/158548809-94de7565-e8a7-403d-be2a-d299ebd78a76.png)

Note that the changes are in green color.

'body': '# Description

- Fixes issue #27578  

**Changes**
- Correct check condition inside `queueWork()`. If `currentWork` is not terminated, the new coming work should be place into `workQueue`.
- When REQUESTED == 0L (`CurrentWork` is completed), update `CurrentWork` to request new message.

**Detailed logic**

Below diagram shows when call receiver client to receive message:

![sync-receiver-logic](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/97088315/158547889-042cedbc-73b2-43fd-98dd-8dd26589e5c6.png) 

Below diagram shows what if current work is completed or timeout:

![work-complete-and-timeout](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/97088315/158548809-94de7565-e8a7-403d-be2a-d299ebd78a76.png)

Note that the changes are in green color.

# All SDK Contribution checklist:

- [x] **CHANGELOG is updated for new features, bug fixes or other significant changes.**

The typical application use case is "obtain_one_iterable -> iterate -> iteration_completed", then repeat,  the cycle is serial.

Even if the application obtains multiple "Iterables", it can iterate only one "Iterable" at a time, which we call "Active-Iterable".  The current "Active-Iterable" has to terminate for the next "Iterable" already in the scope to become "Active-Iterable". So the design was to start the timer only when an Iterable transition to "Active-Iterable"

'body': '# Description

- Fixes issue #27578  

**Changes**
- Correct check condition inside `queueWork()`. If `currentWork` is not terminated, the new coming work should be place into `workQueue`.
- When REQUESTED == 0L (`CurrentWork` is completed), update `CurrentWork` to request new message.

**Detailed logic**

Below diagram shows when call receiver client to receive message:

![sync-receiver-logic](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/97088315/158547889-042cedbc-73b2-43fd-98dd-8dd26589e5c6.png) 

Below diagram shows what if current work is completed or timeout:

![work-complete-and-timeout](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/97088315/158548809-94de7565-e8a7-403d-be2a-d299ebd78a76.png)

Note that the changes are in green color.

We are seeing these ERROR logs all the time in all the apps that talk to service bus.

***Exception or Stack Trace***
```
2022-02-09 14:22:10.361 ERROR 36280 --- [ctor-executor-2] c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel         : connectionId[MF_ee7f60_1644415609117] linkName[cbs] Error in SendLinkHandler. Disposing unconfirmed sends.

TrackingId:abfbe36f1cb3408ca596ba408110e81b_G7, SystemTracker:gateway7, Timestamp:2022-02-09T14:22:10, errorContext[NAMESPACE: servicebus-test-delete-me.servicebus.windows.net. ERROR CONTEXT: N/A, PATH: $cbs, REFERENCE_ID: cbs:sender, LINK_CREDIT: 98]
2022-02-09 14:23:14.948 ERROR 36280 --- [     parallel-6] c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel         : connectionId[MF_ee7f60_1644415609117] linkName[cbs]: Unable to open send and receive link.
```

**To Reproduce**
Leave a connection open without receiving or sending messages for a while.

**Expected behavior**
If this is expected, then this is simply a DEBUG or INFO log and it has to be changed to that. If we need to fix something in our code, then please explain us what we need to change in order to not get these error codes.

The alternative is to suppress all logs coming from c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel, but this would remove any possible true issues that we might have in that class. 

**Setup:**
 - OS: Linux, macOS
 - IDE: IntelliJ
 - Library/Libraries: com.azure:azure-core:1.25.0, com.azure:azure-messaging-servicebus:7.5.2
 - Java version: 11
 - App Server/Environment: Tomcat
 - Frameworks: Spring Boot 

**Additional context**
This is failing within Azure Kubernetes Service and from our development laptops

We are seeing these ERROR logs all the time in all the apps that talk to service bus.

***Exception or Stack Trace***
```
2022-02-09 14:22:10.361 ERROR 36280 --- [ctor-executor-2] c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel         : connectionId[MF_ee7f60_1644415609117] linkName[cbs] Error in SendLinkHandler. Disposing unconfirmed sends.
The connection was inactive for more than the allowed 300000 milliseconds and is closed by container 'LinkTracker'. TrackingId:abfbe36f1cb3408ca596ba408110e81b_G7, SystemTracker:gateway7, Timestamp:2022-02-09T14:22:10, errorContext[NAMESPACE: servicebus-test-delete-me.servicebus.windows.net. ERROR CONTEXT: N/A, PATH: $cbs, REFERENCE_ID: cbs:sender, LINK_CREDIT: 98]
2022-02-09 14:23:14.948 ERROR 36280 --- [     parallel-6] c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel         : connectionId[MF_ee7f60_1644415609117] linkName[cbs]: Unable to open send and receive link.
```

**To Reproduce**
Leave a connection open without receiving or sending messages for a while.

**Expected behavior**
If this is expected, then this is simply a DEBUG or INFO log and it has to be changed to that. If we need to fix something in our code, then please explain us what we need to change in order to not get these error codes.

The alternative is to suppress all logs coming from c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel, but this would remove any possible true issues that we might have in that class. 

**Setup:**
 - OS: Linux, macOS
 - IDE: IntelliJ
 - Library/Libraries: com.azure:azure-core:1.25.0, com.azure:azure-messaging-servicebus:7.5.2
 - Java version: 11
 - App Server/Environment: Tomcat
 - Frameworks: Spring Boot 

**Additional context**
This is failing within Azure Kubernetes Service and from our development laptops

'updated_at': '2022-03-23T17:13:58Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'Memory Leak caused by cloning the message object multuple times causes heap size to grow enormously when the message size is large. 

in class - com.azure.messaging.servicebus.ServiceBusMessageSerializer

https://azuresdkartifacts.blob.core.windows.net/azure-sdk-for-java/test-coverage/azure-messaging-servicebus/com.azure.messaging.servicebus/ServiceBusMessageSerializer.java.html

The line `final byte[] body = brokeredMessage.getBody().toBytes();` copies the message twice and creates an additional byte array which isnt used but exists in memory that bulks up the heap space. 

This situation exacerbates when working with large sized messsages.

All the wrapper-type instances involved "refer" to the same byte array without copying.

>  final byte[] body = brokeredMessage.getBody().toBytes();

At the basic level, there is AmqpAnnotatedMessage owning the byte[] array. Inside [BinaryData.fromBytes](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/8864b50fa484cd4dcb79d8e6e1ddfcf9dc6d10ec/sdk/core/azure-core/src/main/java/com/azure/core/util/BinaryData.java#L373) this gets wrapped in a ByteArrayContent by [reference](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/8864b50fa484cd4dcb79d8e6e1ddfcf9dc6d10ec/sdk/core/azure-core/src/main/java/com/azure/core/implementation/util/ByteArrayContent.java#L29). The toBytes() in ByteArrayContent end up returning the same [reference](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/8864b50fa484cd4dcb79d8e6e1ddfcf9dc6d10ec/sdk/core/azure-core/src/main/java/com/azure/core/implementation/util/ByteArrayContent.java#L44), the `body` local variable refers this. Finally, the same reference (`body`) is passed to amqpMessage.setBody API and there is no copying there as well.', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/comments/1076592063/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'body': '# Description

- Fixes issue #27578  

**Changes**
- Correct check condition inside `queueWork()`. If `currentWork` is not terminated, the new coming work should be place into `workQueue`.
- When REQUESTED == 0L (`CurrentWork` is completed), update `CurrentWork` to request new message.

**Detailed logic**

Below diagram shows when call receiver client to receive message:

![sync-receiver-logic](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/97088315/158547889-042cedbc-73b2-43fd-98dd-8dd26589e5c6.png) 

Below diagram shows what if current work is completed or timeout:

![work-complete-and-timeout](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/97088315/158548809-94de7565-e8a7-403d-be2a-d299ebd78a76.png)

Note that the changes are in green color.

'body': '# Description

- Fixes issue #27578  

**Changes**
- Correct check condition inside `queueWork()`. If `currentWork` is not terminated, the new coming work should be place into `workQueue`.
- When REQUESTED == 0L (`CurrentWork` is completed), update `CurrentWork` to request new message.

**Detailed logic**

Below diagram shows when call receiver client to receive message:

![sync-receiver-logic](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/97088315/158547889-042cedbc-73b2-43fd-98dd-8dd26589e5c6.png) 

Below diagram shows what if current work is completed or timeout:

![work-complete-and-timeout](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/97088315/158548809-94de7565-e8a7-403d-be2a-d299ebd78a76.png)

Note that the changes are in green color.

**To Reproduce**
1. Receive a message from a topic using ServiceBusReceiverClient.
2. Then process the received message. Suppose, it takes a very long time, e.g. 2-3 hours.
3. During the processing time, keep renewing the message lock. Please note that the server message lock time for the topic is maximum 5 minutes. And we are renewing the lock every one minute making sure that it never loses the lock.
4. Once the processing is over, send a new message to the same topic using ServiceBusSenderClient.
5. Exception comes: Cannot send a message when request response channel is disposed

**Expected behavior**

Message should have been sent to topic by using ServiceBusSenderClient without any exception. Even if there is some diconnect between sender and server, SDK should revive the connection automatically. Please note that this error is an intermittent error.

**Setup (please complete the following information):**
 - OS: UNIX
 - IDE: IntelliJ
 - Library/Libraries: com.azure:azure-messaging-servicebus:7.5.1
 - Java version: 8
 - App Server/Environment: Tomcat
 - Frameworks: Spring

**Additional context**
1. Error comes while sending a message after a long processing time.
2. Please note that this error is an intermittent error.
3. Earlier this error was very frequent in our UAT environment. Then as per the suggestion from Microsoft support, we upgraded to the latest SDK azure-messaging-servicebus v7.5.1 and it was fixed for us in UAT environment.
4. '2022-03-17T16:18:29Z', 'closed_at': '2022-03-09T02:17:07Z', 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '## The problem: unrecovered receiver(s)

[Here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/files/8194575/User_Log.xlsx) is the SDK log from a user, experiencing the stopping of one or more partition receivers. The only option was to recover by restarting the pod. Similar incident happened a few times. The log is for one such incident where only 1 out of 4 partitions recovered after a servicing event, and the rest 3 stopped without notifying the application.

_The log file contains the log entries in descending order of timestamp - i.e. the first logline in the file is the latest. Colors are applied to sets of related consecutive loglines to make it easy for human eyes to parse._

The logs show that certain endpoints-closing traffic initiated by the service resulted in SDK entering an unrecoverable state. The design of SDK is to recover from endpoints-closing traffic unless it is associated with a catastrophic event (such as extended service downtime, user network downtime). There is no consistent repro given the service traffic drives it, and NOT ALL closure traffic cause this.

## The problematic service traffic: endpoint-closure events

The following are the SDK internal events in response to endpoint-closure traffic, extracted from the log -

## Reproducing the endpoint-closure traffic events

Since all these SDK events are initiated by the service traffic and notified by the 3rd party ProtonJ library, there is no easy way to produce the same traffic in the same order with similar timing.

Given the limited options, we modified the library code to inject these ProtonJ events in the same order (as appears in the Cx log) with similar delays between events. Approximately 8 out of 10 runs produced the local log that matches with the user logs.

The repro has 3 steps -

1. Create EH with 4 partitions. Keep the EH empty to ensure service is not interfering with event injection (step 3).
2. Run a simple code to connect to 4 partitions using low-level receiver client. Let SDK to open endpoints as usual - connection, sessions, and links to the service. Use the modified library code to cache the ProtonJ objects representing these endpoints and handlers.
3. Use the cached ProtonJ objects to inject the events that otherwise would have been produced in response to real service closure traffic. SDK seems to recover if following conditions are not met -
    - The ordering of events must match.
    - The "timing" (delay) between events must match.

The produced local logs match the user log - including all the exceptions, associated stack trace, and other flow-related logs in the correct logical order. An instance of such a locally produced log is [here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/files/8194609/Local_Log.md).

## Root causing

1. All 3 (out of 4) unrecovered receivers had a similar pattern. Hence focused on one of the unrecovered receivers, the partition 1 receiver.
2. Within the async state machine, identified the subgraph representing the recovery flow of partition 1 receiver.
3. Modified the subgraph's reactor-chain to log reactor terminal event - completion and error.
4. Looked for hanging nodes in the subgraph instance i.e., points in the reactor-chain where the a terminal event didn't emit.

It was observed that [this](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorSession.java#L373) reactive `authroize()` node never terminated i.e., it didn't emit a completion or error terminal signal.

### Confirming the observation

To confirm this is really the problematic node (or root-node of sub-subgraph with the problem), a "timeout" operator is applied after the `authorize` node, which, when expired, unblocked the node in the subgraph that inturns unblocked the recovery path of partition 1 receiver (same for the other two receivers with the similar symptom).

### Digging further down in the subgraph (part 1)

Applying the "timeout" for a node close to the IO makes sense. But it is crucial to understand the network (or any IO) is the immediate bottleneck here.

Hence, continued drilling down the subgraph rooted at `authorize()` and reached this terminal [Sink node](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L320) in RequestResponseChannel::sendWithAck method, and identified that this Sink is never terminated.

The RRChannel tracks the Sink in question [here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L325) in a HashMap, the Sink is terminated

1. If service request scheduling fails,
1. When receiving the corresponding service response,
2. Or at the time of closing the RRChannel object.

Clearly, none of the above routes terminated the Sink, resulting in downstream `authorize()` waiting forever.

### Digging further down in the subgraph (part 2)

With the above understanding, flow results in the three partition receivers (1, 2, and 3) hanging is proven to be below. 

1. From `authorize()`, the RRChannel::sendWithAck is called when the RRChannel was not disposed. It enqueued a [work](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/a7060c45b016da37399106e1adb7f8f2e8a2991d/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L328) (not executed yet) to the ProtonJ message pump thread. The temporary logging we added confirms this call by printing RRChannel's dispose state and ObjectId. 
> 2022-03-05 09:13:02.536 [reactor-executor-1] [INFO] c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel - {"az.sdk.message":"RRChannel::sendWithAck linkName:1_6c9bc5_1646500372433 isDisposed:false ObjectId
:9fc336","connectionId":"MF_f39d21_1646500370415","linkName":"cbs"}
2. Service traffic results in RRChannel's Send and Receive Links closure, marking RRChannel as disposed. The temporary logging we added confirms this.
> 2022-03-05 09:13:02.623 [reactor-executor-1] [DEBUG] c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel - {"az.sdk.message":"Closing request/response channel. ObjectId :9fc336","connectionId":"MF_f39d21_1646500370415","linkName":"cbs"}
3. The connection is not closed yet or closed, but the propagation of the closure event is in progress, and the ProtonJ message pump is healthy; hence it executes the work enqueued by 1. The temporary logging we added shows the RRChannel is already disposed of by this time.
> 2022-03-05 09:13:02.636 [reactor-executor-1] [INFO] c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel - {"az.sdk.message":"RRChannel::sendWithAck -> Dispatcher.invoke linkName:1_6c9bc5_1646500372433 isDisposed:true ObjectId :9fc336","connectionId":"MF_f39d21_1646500370415","linkName":"cbs"}
4. The work attempted to [use](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L345) the disposed ProtonJ Sender object, throwing IllegalStateException; this exception is caught and [logged](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorExecutor.java#L110) by the "global handler" of message pump.
> o.a.q.p.e.HandlerException: java.lang.IllegalStateException: send not allowed after the sender is closed.
	at o.a.q.p.e.impl.EventImpl.dispatch(EventImpl.java:112) ...
5. The above-outlined flow results in the Sink(s) being never terminated, causing `authorize` to wait forever, which inturn results in partition 1, 2 and 3 to never recover.

## The code fix

Now we know the exact reason, the fix is as simple as checking dispose state at the time of "execution".

```java
if (isDisposed() 
    || sendLink.getLocalState() == EndpointState.CLOSED 
    || receiveLink.getLocalState() == EndpointState.CLOSED) {
    sink.error(new IllegalStateException("Cannot send a message when request response channel is disposed."));
    return;
}
```

Emitting IllegalStateException like this during "execution" aligns with the similar error emission from [here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L298) at the time of "scheduling". 

Note that this fix will not result in the faulted low-level receiver resuming. Instead, once the fix is in, the application using a "low-level receiver" will get notified about the error, upon which the application can recreate the receiver. 

For the application using "processor receiver", it currently hangs. But once the fix is in, the processor internally handles the error from it's "low-level receiver" and recovers for the user.

## Thoughts:

Look at other places in the SDK that can be affected in the same fashion.

## References:

The service bus user running into this specific race case: https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/23398

'created_at': '2022-03-16T22:26:09Z', 'updated_at': '2022-03-17T01:22:06Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '## Background

Two customer tickets reported that the ProtonJ error "no current delivery" appeared in the logs, but when it happened in the lower layer, it activated a code path in the upper layer that triggered a reliability issue;[ this-pr](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/24141) addressed it.

This ticket is created so that we can focus on ProtonJ error "no current delivery" .

## Root causing

As part of [this](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/27482) investigation, we learned that it is possible that the ProtonJ object state can be mutated (e.g disposed) after the "scheduling" of work to the message-pump but before the actual "execution" of the work. 

Sketching the control flow, it looks like the reason for "no current delivery"  is such a mutation; the flow appears to be below -


1. ProtonJ Receiver received a delivery. It updated its __current_ pointer to refer to this delivery then handed it over to ReceiveLinkHandler.
2. ReceiveLinkHandler [enqueues](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/0ddca1176c70abd30ab69d71c219f487aef4d0d3/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/handler/ReceiveLinkHandler.java#L164) the delivery to deliveries-Flux. 
3. The async-chain attached to deliveries-Flux [emits](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/0ddca1176c70abd30ab69d71c219f487aef4d0d3/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorReceiver.java#L82) the delivery to ReactorReceiver. 
4. The ReactorReceiver "[schedule](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/0ddca1176c70abd30ab69d71c219f487aef4d0d3/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorReceiver.java#L85)" a work to message-pump thread to decode this delivery.
5. The async-chain is waiting asynchronously for the Sink to complete. The completion happens only when scheduled work in 4 "executes" in the future.
6. The service traffic closed the amqp-receive-link, inturn [frees](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/0ddca1176c70abd30ab69d71c219f487aef4d0d3/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorReceiver.java#L347) the ProtonJ Receiver using message-pump thread. Note: the user-work in 4 and proton-j work in 6 does not execute strictly in FIFO order (two different pipes drive it), but the serial execution is guaranteed.
7. As part of freeing the ProtonJ Receiver, the ProtonJ library frees the delivery (that 4 refers to), settling the delivery and advancing the __current_ pointer. The __current_ become null.
8. ReceiveLinkHandler [emits](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/0ddca1176c70abd30ab69d71c219f487aef4d0d3/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/handler/ReceiveLinkHandler.java#L237) completion-event to deliveries-Flux, but it gets deferred because the Sink for the last event (5) is yet to be complete.
9. Work scheduled in 4 executes, but since __current_ is null and not the one the work is referring to, ProtonJ throws "no current delivery"

The exception in 9 goes to global error handling as an unhandled exception. Three 3 issues -

a. The Sink in 5 never errored
b. Hence the completion-event in 8 never emits (because queued after a)
c. The unhandled exception forces the parent amqp-connection to close  

The good thing is, there is no one [downstream](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/0ddca1176c70abd30ab69d71c219f487aef4d0d3/sdk/eventhubs/azure-messaging-eventhubs/src/main/java/com/azure/messaging/eventhubs/implementation/AmqpReceiveLinkProcessor.java#L286) waiting to react to the "terminal event" from a (or b) to happen. But c is concerning because the closure of one amqp-receiver-link combined with the race resulted in amqp-connection to close, which means it causes all other healthy amqp-receiver-links in the same amqp-connection to disconnect from service. 

## Fix

Again fix is simple as [this](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/27482) ticket, i.e. do a deferred check for disposal of the Receiver so that the side effect is limited to that specific Receiver and not bypassed to the parent connection.


## References

The customer tickets - https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24575 and https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/26975

But c is concerning because the closure of one amqp-receiver-link combined with the race resulted in amqp-connection to close, which means it causes all other healthy amqp-receiver-links in the same amqp-connection to disconnect from service. 

## Fix

Again fix is simple as [this](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/27482) ticket, i.e. do a deferred check for disposal of the Receiver so that the side effect is limited to that specific Receiver and not bypassed to the parent connection.


## References

The customer tickets - https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24575 and https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/26975

'updated_at': '2022-03-09T02:17:07Z', 'closed_at': '2022-03-09T02:17:07Z', 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '### TL;DR

If there is a race in `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` that results in concurrent throwing of `ClosedChannelException`, then reactive spec 1.3 may get violated and parts of SDK may not be able to recover.

### Long version:

#### Purpose of ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` is a private method that the public  API (scoped to implementation) `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` uses. Different parts of the Amqp library uses `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` API from multiple threads to schedule works (that touches ProtonJ thread-unsafe objects) to single-threaded ProtonJ message pump.

#### Concurrency safety on ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The data structure (ConcurrentLinkedQueue) used inside the `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` method is thread-safe and the pipe API for message pump notification is concurrent safe as well. Given `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` belongs to the hot path, these concurrent safeties help avoid marking the method `synchronized`.

#### Exceptions in ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The two expected exceptions from the guarding section of this method are - `RejectedExecutionException` REE (related to concurrency) and `IOException` IOE (if message pump pipe is closed). In places where the Amqp library invokes this method, the two exceptions are propagated to the Reactor pipeline (e.g., via Sink.emitError) for downstream to take appropriate action. 

A specific exception handled inside this method (i.e., an exception won't leave this method) is `ClosedChannelException` (CCE). CCE indicates that the thread executing the invoke method got interrupted, and as a result, JVM closes the message pump pipe. Therefore any resources that rely on the single-threaded ProtonJ message pump (attached to this pipe) are unusable. When this happens, a shutdown signal is emitted via `Sink.One` (which is by design can be completed once) on which the `ReactorConnection` object listen.

#### Issue related to signaling in ReactorDispatcher::invoke

In rare cases, MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads can concurrently bypass the guard check (which otherwise would have thrown `RejectedExecutionException` or `IOException`) and enter invoke method, then all those threads run into CCE. (Any threads coming in the future will get `IOException` since the pipe is closed.)

In the case of MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads, two things can happen -.

1. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal to `Sink.One` "concurrently", which violates Reactor Spec. Rule 1.3. 
2. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal  to `Sink.One` "serially"; by design, the Reactor library ignores the second or later emissions.

When `#1` happens, in some cases, we have seen it is going to Reactor global `onErrorDropped` hook, which becomes simply a log entry. Here is such an example log https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24762. The exact reason for going into global-hook needs to be identified, but the point is, we must not violate the spec 1.3.

> Following is the stack trace proving spec 1.3 violation due to concurrent `ClosedChannelException` (CCE).

```
reactor.core.Exceptions$ErrorCallbackNotImplemented: reactor.core.publisher.Sinks$EmissionException: Spec. Rule 1.3 - onSubscribe, onNext, onError and onComplete signaled to a Subscriber MUST be signaled serially.
Caused by: reactor.core.publisher.Sinks$EmissionException: Spec. Rule 1.3 - onSubscribe, onNext, onError and onComplete signaled to a Subscriber MUST be signaled serially.
	at reactor.core.publisher.InternalEmptySink.emitError(InternalEmptySink.java:76)
	at com.azure.core.amqp.implementation.ReactorDispatcher.signalWorkQueue(ReactorDispatcher.java:130)
	at com.azure.core.amqp.implementation.ReactorDispatcher.invoke(ReactorDispatcher.java:94)
	at com.azure.core.amqp.implementation.RequestResponseChannel.lambda$closeAsync$12(RequestResponseChannel.java:230)
	at reactor.core.publisher.MonoRunnable.subscribe(MonoRunnable.java:49)
	at reactor.core.publisher.Mono.subscribe(Mono.java:4338)
        ....
```

When `#2` happens, it is as if those additional signals are lost; the `ReactorConnection` care only about the first Shutdown signal, there are no consumption of any future emitted values.

### Proposal:

The fix should make sure -
1. `invoke` do not violate spec 1.3,
2. the signal emission happens only once,
 3. to treat "interrupted" threads (those lost the battle of emission) just like any future threads receiving `RejectedExecutionException` under pipe close. Ideally, the downstream (callers of `invoke`) get to handle the side effect rather than waiting forever for a signal.

Application stops on error. 

***Exception or Stack Trace***
Two different Stack Traces in file from two different servers, from the same connection error, same datetime.

**To Reproduce**
Happens one a week or so, randomly in multiple locations, cant reproduce easily.

**Expected behavior**
Application can't close with error, it should retry on error.

'https://api.github.com/users/conniey/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# Description

* Currently, we are adding the handler twice, once as a child handler of the reactor and second time as an event handled by the global reactor.  So, on an event, this handler would be called twice (https://github.com/apache/qpid-proton-j/blob/main/proton-j/src/main/java/org/apache/qpid/proton/reactor/impl/ReactorImpl.java#L291-L292).  This wouldn't be a problem if CustomIOHandler extended from BaseHandler, `onUnhandled` is a no-op, however, the IOHandler.onUnhandled class performs functions to free the selector, etc. Invoking it twice would lead to, probably, unexpected behaviour.
*  Do not override the globalHandler. It's not necessary and from the documentation, probably not what we want.

/cc @Azure/azsdk-sb-java

'https://api.github.com/users/conniey/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '# Description

* Fixes issue where lastEnqueuedEventProperties is null for an empty window. When no events arrive during the windowTimeout period, an empty batch is emitted. In this case, there are no lastEnqueuedEventProperties to fetch, and users encounter an NPE.  Uses the previously seen lastEnqueuedEventProperties because there have not been any seen updates since then.
* Adds tests.

Fixes #27121

'2022-03-08T05:56:03Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '## The problem: unrecovered receiver(s)

[Here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/files/8194575/User_Log.xlsx) is the SDK log from a user, experiencing the stopping of one or more partition receivers. The only option was to recover by restarting the pod. Similar incident happened a few times. The log is for one such incident where only 1 out of 4 partitions recovered after a servicing event, and the rest 3 stopped without notifying the application.

_The log file contains the log entries in descending order of timestamp - i.e. the first logline in the file is the latest. Colors are applied to sets of related consecutive loglines to make it easy for human eyes to parse._

The logs show that certain endpoints-closing traffic initiated by the service resulted in SDK entering an unrecoverable state. The design of SDK is to recover from endpoints-closing traffic unless it is associated with a catastrophic event (such as extended service downtime, user network downtime). There is no consistent repro given the service traffic drives it, and NOT ALL closure traffic cause this.

## The problematic service traffic: endpoint-closure events

The following are the SDK internal events in response to endpoint-closure traffic, extracted from the log -

<details><summary>expand:</summary>

```

## Reproducing the endpoint-closure traffic events

Since all these SDK events are initiated by the service traffic and notified by the 3rd party ProtonJ library, there is no easy way to produce the same traffic in the same order with similar timing.

Given the limited options, we modified the library code to inject these ProtonJ events in the same order (as appears in the Cx log) with similar delays between events. Approximately 8 out of 10 runs produced the local log that matches with the user logs.

The repro has 3 steps -

1. Create EH with 4 partitions. Keep the EH empty to ensure service is not interfering with event injection (step 3).
2. Run a simple code to connect to 4 partitions using low-level receiver client. Let SDK to open endpoints as usual - connection, sessions, and links to the service. Use the modified library code to cache the ProtonJ objects representing these endpoints and handlers.
3. Use the cached ProtonJ objects to inject the events that otherwise would have been produced in response to real service closure traffic. SDK seems to recover if following conditions are not met -
    - The ordering of events must match.
    - The "timing" (delay) between events must match.

The produced local logs match the user log - including all the exceptions, associated stack trace, and other flow-related logs in the correct logical order. An instance of such a locally produced log is [here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/files/8194609/Local_Log.md).

## Root causing

1. All 3 (out of 4) unrecovered receivers had a similar pattern. Hence focused on one of the unrecovered receivers, the partition 1 receiver.
2. Within the async state machine, identified the subgraph representing the recovery flow of partition 1 receiver.
3. Modified the subgraph's reactor-chain to log reactor terminal event - completion and error.
4. Looked for hanging nodes in the subgraph instance i.e., points in the reactor-chain where the a terminal event didn't emit.

It was observed that [this](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorSession.java#L373) reactive `authroize()` node never terminated i.e., it didn't emit a completion or error terminal signal.

### Confirming the observation

To confirm this is really the problematic node (or root-node of sub-subgraph with the problem), a "timeout" operator is applied after the `authorize` node, which, when expired, unblocked the node in the subgraph that inturns unblocked the recovery path of partition 1 receiver (same for the other two receivers with the similar symptom).

### Digging further down in the subgraph (part 1)

Applying the "timeout" for a node close to the IO makes sense. But it is crucial to understand the network (or any IO) is the immediate bottleneck here.

Hence, continued drilling down the subgraph rooted at `authorize()` and reached this terminal [Sink node](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L320) in RequestResponseChannel::sendWithAck method, and identified that this Sink is never terminated.

The RRChannel tracks the Sink in question [here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L325) in a HashMap, the Sink is terminated

1. If service request scheduling fails,
1. When receiving the corresponding service response,
2. Or at the time of closing the RRChannel object.

Clearly, none of the above routes terminated the Sink, resulting in downstream `authorize()` waiting forever.

### Digging further down in the subgraph (part 2)

With the above understanding, flow results in the three partition receivers (1, 2, and 3) hanging is proven to be below. 

1. From `authorize()`, the RRChannel::sendWithAck is called when the RRChannel was not disposed. It enqueued a [work](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/a7060c45b016da37399106e1adb7f8f2e8a2991d/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L328) (not executed yet) to the ProtonJ message pump thread. The temporary logging we added confirms this call by printing RRChannel's dispose state and ObjectId. 
> 2022-03-05 09:13:02.536 [reactor-executor-1] [INFO] c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel - {"az.sdk.message":"RRChannel::sendWithAck linkName:1_6c9bc5_1646500372433 isDisposed:false ObjectId
:9fc336","connectionId":"MF_f39d21_1646500370415","linkName":"cbs"}
2. Service traffic results in RRChannel's Send and Receive Links closure, marking RRChannel as disposed. The temporary logging we added confirms this.
> 2022-03-05 09:13:02.623 [reactor-executor-1] [DEBUG] c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel - {"az.sdk.message":"Closing request/response channel. ObjectId :9fc336","connectionId":"MF_f39d21_1646500370415","linkName":"cbs"}
3. The connection is not closed yet or closed, but the propagation of the closure event is in progress, and the ProtonJ message pump is healthy; hence it executes the work enqueued by 1. The temporary logging we added shows the RRChannel is already disposed of by this time.
> 2022-03-05 09:13:02.636 [reactor-executor-1] [INFO] c.a.c.a.i.RequestResponseChannel - {"az.sdk.message":"RRChannel::sendWithAck -> Dispatcher.invoke linkName:1_6c9bc5_1646500372433 isDisposed:true ObjectId :9fc336","connectionId":"MF_f39d21_1646500370415","linkName":"cbs"}
4. The work attempted to [use](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L345) the disposed ProtonJ Sender object, throwing IllegalStateException; this exception is caught and [logged](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/ReactorExecutor.java#L110) by the "global handler" of message pump.
> o.a.q.p.e.HandlerException: java.lang.IllegalStateException: send not allowed after the sender is closed.
	at o.a.q.p.e.impl.EventImpl.dispatch(EventImpl.java:112) ...
5. The above-outlined flow results in the Sink(s) being never terminated, causing `authorize` to wait forever, which inturn results in partition 1, 2 and 3 to never recover.

## The code fix

Now we know the exact reason, the fix is as simple as checking dispose state at the time of "execution".

```java
if (isDisposed() 
    || sendLink.getLocalState() == EndpointState.CLOSED 
    || receiveLink.getLocalState() == EndpointState.CLOSED) {
    sink.error(new IllegalStateException("Cannot send a message when request response channel is disposed."));
    return;
}
```

Emitting IllegalStateException like this during "execution" aligns with the similar error emission from [here](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/blob/400f6198aaf1258ec0b57a2bebc59ff9e7ac81ae/sdk/core/azure-core-amqp/src/main/java/com/azure/core/amqp/implementation/RequestResponseChannel.java#L298) at the time of "scheduling". 

Note that this fix will not result in the faulted low-level receiver resuming. Instead, once the fix is in, the application using a "low-level receiver" will get notified about the error, upon which the application can recreate the receiver. 

For the application using "processor receiver", it currently hangs. But once the fix is in, the processor internally handles the error from it's "low-level receiver" and recovers for the user.

## Thoughts:

Look at other places in the SDK that can be affected in the same fashion.

## References:

The service bus user running into this specific race case: https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/23398

'comments': 0, 'created_at': '2022-02-26T00:19:25Z', 'updated_at': '2022-02-26T00:19:25Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'MEMBER', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': '### TL;DR

If there is a race in `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` that results in concurrent throwing of `ClosedChannelException`, then reactive spec 1.3 may get violated and parts of SDK may not be able to recover.

### Long version:

#### Purpose of ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` is a private method that the public  API (scoped to implementation) `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` uses. Different parts of the Amqp library uses `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` API from multiple threads to schedule works (that touches ProtonJ thread-unsafe objects) to single-threaded ProtonJ message pump.

#### Concurrency safety on ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The data structure (ConcurrentLinkedQueue) used inside the `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` method is thread-safe and the pipe API for message pump pipe notification is concurrent safe as well. Given `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` belongs to the hot path, these concurrent safeties help avoid marking the method `synchronized`.

#### Exceptions in ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The two expected exceptions from the guarding section of this method are - `RejectedExecutionException` REE (related to concurrency) and `IOException` IOE (if message pump pipe is closed). In places where the Amqp library invokes this method, the two exceptions are propagated to the Reactor pipeline (e.g., via Sink.emitError) for downstream to take appropriate action. 

A specific exception handled inside this method (i.e., an exception won't leave this method) is `ClosedChannelException` (CCE). CCE indicates that the thread executing the invoke method got interrupted, and as a result, JVM closes the message pump pipe. Therefore any resources that rely on the single-threaded ProtonJ message pump (attached to this pipe) are unusable. When this happens, a shutdown signal is emitted via `Sink.One` (which is by design can be completed once) on which the `ReactorConnection` object listen.

#### Issue related to signaling in ReactorDispatcher::invoke

In rare cases, MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads can concurrently bypass the guard check (which otherwise would have thrown `RejectedExecutionException` or `IOException`) and enter invoke method, then all those threads run into CCE. (Any threads coming in the future will get `IOException` since the pipe is closed.)

In the case of MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads, two things can happen -.

1. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal to `Sink.One` "concurrently", which violates Reactor Spec. Rule 1.3. 
2. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal  to `Sink.One` "serially"; by design, the Reactor library ignores the second or later emissions.

When `#1` happens, in some cases, we have seen it is going to Reactor global `onErrorDropped` hook, which becomes simply a log entry. Here is such an example log https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24762. The exact reason for going into global-hook needs to be identified, but the point is, we must not violate the spec 1.3.

When `#2` happens, it is as if those additional signals are lost; the `ReactorConnection` care only about the first Shutdown signal, there are no consumption of any future emitted values.

### Proposal:

The fix should make sure -
1. `invoke` do not violate spec 1.3,
2. the signal emission happens only once,
 3. to treat "interrupted" threads (those lost the battle of emission) just like any future threads receiving `RejectedExecutionException` under pipe close. Ideally, the downstream (callers of `invoke`) get to handle the side effect rather than waiting forever for a signal.
