'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### TL;DR

If there is a race in `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` that results in concurrent throwing of `ClosedChannelException`, then reactive spec 1.3 may get violated and parts of SDK may not be able to recover. The PR fixes this.

### Long version:

#### Purpose of ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` is a private method that the public  API (scoped to implementation) `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` uses. Different parts of the Amqp library uses `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` API from multiple threads to schedule works (that touches ProtonJ thread-unsafe objects) to single-threaded ProtonJ message pump.

#### Concurrency saftly on ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The data structure (ConcurrentLinkedQueue) used inside the `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` method is thread-safe and the pipe API for message pump pipe notification is concurrent safe as well. Given `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` belongs to the hot path, these concurrent safeties help avoid marking the method `synchronized`.

#### Exceptions in ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The two expected exceptions from the guarding section of this method are - `RejectedExecutionException` REE (related to concurrency) and `IOException` IOE (if message pump pipe is closed). In places where the Amqp library invokes this method, the two exceptions are propagated to the Reactor pipeline (e.g., via Sink.emitError) for downstream to take appropriate action. 

A specific exception handled inside this method (i.e., an exception won't leave this method) is `ClosedChannelException` (CCE). CCE indicates that the thread executing the invoke method got interrupted, and as a result, JVM closes the message pump pipe. Therefore any resources that rely on the single-threaded ProtonJ message pump (attached to this pipe) are unusable. When this happens, a shutdown signal is emitted via `Sink.One` (which is by design can be completed once) on which the `ReactorConnection` object listen.

#### Findings related to signaling in ReactorDispatcher::invoke (the issues)

In rare cases, MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads can concurrently bypass the guard check (which otherwise would have thrown `RejectedExecutionException` or `IOException`) and enter invoke method, then all those threads run into CCE. (Any threads coming in the future will get `IOException` since the pipe is closed.)

In the case of MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads, two things can happen -.

1. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal to `Sink.One` "concurrently", which violates Reactor Spec. Rule 1.3. 
2. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal  to `Sink.One` "serially"; by design, the Reactor library ignores the second or later emissions.

When `#1` happens, in some cases, we have seen it is going to Reactor global `onErrorDropped` hook, which becomes simply a log entry. Here is such an example log https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24762. The exact reason for going into global-hook needs to be identified, but the point is, we must not violate the spec 1.3.

When `#2` happens, it is as if those additional signals are lost; the `ReactorConnection` care only about the first Shutdown signal, there are no consumption of any future emitted values.

### Proposal:

The fix should make sure -
1. `invoke` do not violate spec 1.3,
2. the signal emission happens only once,
 3. to treat "interrupted" threads (those lost the battle of emission) just like any future threads receiving `RejectedExecutionException` under pipe close. Ideally, the downstream (callers of `invoke`) get to handle the side effect rather than waiting forever for a signal.

'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### TL;DR

If there is a race in `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` that results in concurrent throwing of `ClosedChannelException`, then reactive spec 1.3 may get violated and parts of SDK may not be able to recover. The PR fixes this.

### Long version:

#### Purpose of ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` is a private method that the public  API (scoped to implementation) `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` uses. Different parts of the Amqp library uses `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` API from multiple threads to schedule works (that touches ProtonJ thread-unsafe objects) to single-threaded ProtonJ message pump.

#### Concurrency saftly on ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The data structure (ConcurrentLinkedQueue) used inside the `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` method is thread-safe and the pipe API for message pump pipe notification is concurrent safe as well. Given `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` belongs to the hot path, these concurrent safeties help avoid marking the method `synchronized`.

#### Exceptions in ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The two expected exceptions from the guarding section of this method are - `RejectedExecutionException` REE (related to concurrency) and `IOException` IOE (if message pump pipe is closed). In places where the Amqp library invokes this method, the two exceptions are propagated to the Reactor pipeline (e.g., via Sink.emitError) for downstream to take appropriate action. 

A specific exception handled inside this method (i.e., an exception won't leave this method) is `ClosedChannelException` (CCE). CCE indicates that the thread executing the invoke method got interrupted, and as a result, JVM closes the message pump pipe. Therefore any resources that rely on the single-threaded ProtonJ message pump (attached to this pipe) are unusable. When this happens, a shutdown signal is emitted via `Sink.One` (which is by design can be completed once) on which the `ReactorConnection` object listen.

#### Findings related to signaling in ReactorDispatcher::invoke (the issues)

In rare cases, MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads can concurrently bypass the guard check (which otherwise would have thrown `RejectedExecutionException` or `IOException`) and enter invoke method, then all those threads run into CCE. (Any threads coming in the future will get `IOException` since the pipe is closed.)

In the case of MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads, two things can happen -.

1. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal to `Sink.One` "concurrently", which violates Reactor Spec. Rule 1.3. 
2. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal  to `Sink.One` "serially"; by design, the Reactor library ignores the second or later emissions.

When `#1` happens, in some cases, we have seen it is going to Reactor global `onErrorDropped` hook, which becomes simply a log entry. Here is such an example log https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24762. The exact reason for going into global-hook needs to be identified, but the point is, we must not violate the spec 1.3.

When `#2` happens, it is as if those additional signals are lost; the `ReactorConnection` care only about the first Shutdown signal, there are no consumption of any future emitted values.

### Proposal:

The fix should make sure -
1. `invoke` do not violate spec 1.3,
2. the signal emission happens only once,
 3. to treat "interrupted" threads (those lost the battle of emission) just like any future threads receiving `RejectedExecutionException` under pipe close. Ideally, the downstream (callers of `invoke`) get to handle the side effect rather than waiting forever for a signal.

'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### TL;DR

If there is a race in `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` that results in concurrent throwing of `ClosedChannelException`, then reactive spec 1.3 may get violated and parts of SDK may not be able to recover. The PR fixes this.

### Long version:

#### Purpose of ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` is a private method that the public  API (scoped to implementation) `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` uses. Different parts of the Amqp library uses `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` API from multiple threads to schedule works (that touches ProtonJ thread-unsafe objects) to single-threaded ProtonJ message pump.

#### Concurrency saftly on ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The data structure (ConcurrentLinkedQueue) used inside the `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` method is thread-safe and the pipe API for message pump pipe notification is concurrent safe as well. Given `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` belongs to the hot path, these concurrent safeties help avoid marking the method `synchronized`.

#### Exceptions in ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The two expected exceptions from the guarding section of this method are - `RejectedExecutionException` REE (related to concurrency) and `IOException` IOE (if message pump pipe is closed). In places where the Amqp library invokes this method, the two exceptions are propagated to the Reactor pipeline (e.g., via Sink.emitError) for downstream to take appropriate action. 

A specific exception handled inside this method (i.e., an exception won't leave this method) is `ClosedChannelException` (CCE). CCE indicates that the thread executing the invoke method got interrupted, and as a result, JVM closes the message pump pipe. Therefore any resources that rely on the single-threaded ProtonJ message pump (attached to this pipe) are unusable. When this happens, a shutdown signal is emitted via `Sink.One` (which is by design can be completed once) on which the `ReactorConnection` object listen.

#### Findings related to signaling in ReactorDispatcher::invoke (the issues)

In rare cases, MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads can concurrently bypass the guard check (which otherwise would have thrown `RejectedExecutionException` or `IOException`) and enter invoke method, then all those threads run into CCE. (Any threads coming in the future will get `IOException` since the pipe is closed.)

In the case of MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads, two things can happen -.

1. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal to `Sink.One` "concurrently", which violates Reactor Spec. Rule 1.3. 
2. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal  to `Sink.One` "serially"; by design, the Reactor library ignores the second or later emissions.

When `#1` happens, in some cases, we have seen it is going to Reactor global `onErrorDropped` hook, which becomes simply a log entry. Here is such an example log https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24762. The exact reason for going into global-hook needs to be identified, but the point is, we must not violate the spec 1.3.

When `#2` happens, it is as if those additional signals are lost; the `ReactorConnection` care only about the first Shutdown signal, there are no consumption of any future emitted values.

### Proposal:

The fix should make sure -
1. `invoke` do not violate spec 1.3,
2. the signal emission happens only once,
 3. to treat "interrupted" threads (those lost the battle of emission) just like any future threads receiving `RejectedExecutionException` under pipe close. Ideally, the downstream (callers of `invoke`) get to handle the side effect rather than waiting forever for a signal.

'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### TL;DR

If there is a race in `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` that results in concurrent throwing of `ClosedChannelException`, then reactive spec 1.3 may get violated and parts of SDK may not be able to recover. The PR fixes this.

### Long version:

#### Purpose of ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` is a private method that the public  API (scoped to implementation) `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` uses. Different parts of the Amqp library uses `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` API from multiple threads to schedule works (that touches ProtonJ thread-unsafe objects) to single-threaded ProtonJ message pump.

#### Concurrency saftly on ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The data structure (ConcurrentLinkedQueue) used inside the `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` method is thread-safe and the pipe API for message pump pipe notification is concurrent safe as well. Given `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` belongs to the hot path, these concurrent safeties help avoid marking the method `synchronized`.

#### Exceptions in ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The two expected exceptions from the guarding section of this method are - `RejectedExecutionException` REE (related to concurrency) and `IOException` IOE (if message pump pipe is closed). In places where the Amqp library invokes this method, the two exceptions are propagated to the Reactor pipeline (e.g., via Sink.emitError) for downstream to take appropriate action. 

A specific exception handled inside this method (i.e., an exception won't leave this method) is `ClosedChannelException` (CCE). CCE indicates that the thread executing the invoke method got interrupted, and as a result, JVM closes the message pump pipe. Therefore any resources that rely on the single-threaded ProtonJ message pump (attached to this pipe) are unusable. When this happens, a shutdown signal is emitted via `Sink.One` (which is by design can be completed once) on which the `ReactorConnection` object listen.

#### Findings related to signaling in ReactorDispatcher::invoke (the issues)

In rare cases, MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads can concurrently bypass the guard check (which otherwise would have thrown `RejectedExecutionException` or `IOException`) and enter invoke method, then all those threads run into CCE. (Any threads coming in the future will get `IOException` since the pipe is closed.)

In the case of MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads, two things can happen -.

1. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal to `Sink.One` "concurrently", which violates Reactor Spec. Rule 1.3. 
2. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal  to `Sink.One` "serially"; by design, the Reactor library ignores the second or later emissions.

When `#1` happens, in some cases, we have seen it is going to Reactor global `onErrorDropped` hook, which becomes simply a log entry. Here is such an example log https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24762. The exact reason for going into global-hook needs to be identified, but the point is, we must not violate the spec 1.3.

When `#2` happens, it is as if those additional signals are lost; the `ReactorConnection` care only about the first Shutdown signal, there are no consumption of any future emitted values.

### Proposal:

The fix should make sure -
1. `invoke` do not violate spec 1.3,
2. the signal emission happens only once,
 3. to treat "interrupted" threads (those lost the battle of emission) just like any future threads receiving `RejectedExecutionException` under pipe close. Ideally, the downstream (callers of `invoke`) get to handle the side effect rather than waiting forever for a signal.

'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### TL;DR

If there is a race in `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` that results in concurrent throwing of `ClosedChannelException`, then reactive spec 1.3 may get violated and parts of SDK may not be able to recover. The PR fixes this.

### Long version:

#### Purpose of ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` is a private method that the public  API (scoped to implementation) `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` uses. Different parts of the Amqp library uses `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` API from multiple threads to schedule works (that touches ProtonJ thread-unsafe objects) to single-threaded ProtonJ message pump.

#### Concurrency saftly on ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The data structure (ConcurrentLinkedQueue) used inside the `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` method is thread-safe and the pipe API for message pump pipe notification is concurrent safe as well. Given `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` belongs to the hot path, these concurrent safeties help avoid marking the method `synchronized`.

#### Exceptions in ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The two expected exceptions from the guarding section of this method are - `RejectedExecutionException` REE (related to concurrency) and `IOException` IOE (if message pump pipe is closed). In places where the Amqp library invokes this method, the two exceptions are propagated to the Reactor pipeline (e.g., via Sink.emitError) for downstream to take appropriate action. 

A specific exception handled inside this method (i.e., an exception won't leave this method) is `ClosedChannelException` (CCE). CCE indicates that the thread executing the invoke method got interrupted, and as a result, JVM closes the message pump pipe. Therefore any resources that rely on the single-threaded ProtonJ message pump (attached to this pipe) are unusable. When this happens, a shutdown signal is emitted via `Sink.One` (which is by design can be completed once) on which the `ReactorConnection` object listen.

#### Findings related to signaling in ReactorDispatcher::invoke (the issues)

In rare cases, MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads can concurrently bypass the guard check (which otherwise would have thrown `RejectedExecutionException` or `IOException`) and enter invoke method, then all those threads run into CCE. (Any threads coming in the future will get `IOException` since the pipe is closed.)

In the case of MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads, two things can happen -.

1. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal to `Sink.One` "concurrently", which violates Reactor Spec. Rule 1.3. 
2. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal  to `Sink.One` "serially"; by design, the Reactor library ignores the second or later emissions.

When `#1` happens, in some cases, we have seen it is going to Reactor global `onErrorDropped` hook, which becomes simply a log entry. Here is such an example log https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24762. The exact reason for going into global-hook needs to be identified, but the point is, we must not violate the spec 1.3.

When `#2` happens, it is as if those additional signals are lost; the `ReactorConnection` care only about the first Shutdown signal, there are no consumption of any future emitted values.

### Proposal:

The fix should make sure -
1. `invoke` do not violate spec 1.3,
2. the signal emission happens only once,
 3. to treat "interrupted" threads (those lost the battle of emission) just like any future threads receiving `RejectedExecutionException` under pipe close. Ideally, the downstream (callers of `invoke`) get to handle the side effect rather than waiting forever for a signal.

'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### TL;DR

If there is a race in `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` that results in concurrent throwing of `ClosedChannelException`, then reactive spec 1.3 may get violated and parts of SDK may not be able to recover. The PR fixes this.

### Long version:

#### Purpose of ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` is a private method that the public  API (scoped to implementation) `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` uses. Different parts of the Amqp library uses `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` API from multiple threads to schedule works (that touches ProtonJ thread-unsafe objects) to single-threaded ProtonJ message pump.

#### Concurrency saftly on ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The data structure (ConcurrentLinkedQueue) used inside the `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` method is thread-safe and the pipe API for message pump pipe notification is concurrent safe as well. Given `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` belongs to the hot path, these concurrent safeties help avoid marking the method `synchronized`.

#### Exceptions in ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The two expected exceptions from the guarding section of this method are - `RejectedExecutionException` REE (related to concurrency) and `IOException` IOE (if message pump pipe is closed). In places where the Amqp library invokes this method, the two exceptions are propagated to the Reactor pipeline (e.g., via Sink.emitError) for downstream to take appropriate action. 

A specific exception handled inside this method (i.e., an exception won't leave this method) is `ClosedChannelException` (CCE). CCE indicates that the thread executing the invoke method got interrupted, and as a result, JVM closes the message pump pipe. Therefore any resources that rely on the single-threaded ProtonJ message pump (attached to this pipe) are unusable. When this happens, a shutdown signal is emitted via `Sink.One` (which is by design can be completed once) on which the `ReactorConnection` object listen.

#### Findings related to signaling in ReactorDispatcher::invoke (the issues)

In rare cases, MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads can concurrently bypass the guard check (which otherwise would have thrown `RejectedExecutionException` or `IOException`) and enter invoke method, then all those threads run into CCE. (Any threads coming in the future will get `IOException` since the pipe is closed.)

In the case of MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads, two things can happen -.

1. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal to `Sink.One` "concurrently", which violates Reactor Spec. Rule 1.3. 
2. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal  to `Sink.One` "serially"; by design, the Reactor library ignores the second or later emissions.

When `#1` happens, in some cases, we have seen it is going to Reactor global `onErrorDropped` hook, which becomes simply a log entry. Here is such an example log https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24762. The exact reason for going into global-hook needs to be identified, but the point is, we must not violate the spec 1.3.

When `#2` happens, it is as if those additional signals are lost; the `ReactorConnection` care only about the first Shutdown signal, there are no consumption of any future emitted values.

### Proposal:

The fix should make sure -
1. `invoke` do not violate spec 1.3,
2. the signal emission happens only once,
 3. to treat "interrupted" threads (those lost the battle of emission) just like any future threads receiving `RejectedExecutionException` under pipe close. Ideally, the downstream (callers of `invoke`) get to handle the side effect rather than waiting forever for a signal.

'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/anuchandy/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': '### TL;DR

If there is a race in `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` that results in concurrent throwing of `ClosedChannelException`, then reactive spec 1.3 may get violated and parts of SDK may not be able to recover. The PR fixes this.

### Long version:

#### Purpose of ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` is a private method that the public  API (scoped to implementation) `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` uses. Different parts of the Amqp library uses `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` API from multiple threads to schedule works (that touches ProtonJ thread-unsafe objects) to single-threaded ProtonJ message pump.

#### Concurrency saftly on ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The data structure (ConcurrentLinkedQueue) used inside the `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` method is thread-safe and the pipe API for message pump pipe notification is concurrent safe as well. Given `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` belongs to the hot path, these concurrent safeties help avoid marking the method `synchronized`.

#### Exceptions in ReactorDispatcher::invoke

The two expected exceptions from the guarding section of this method are - `RejectedExecutionException` REE (related to concurrency) and `IOException` IOE (if message pump pipe is closed). In places where the Amqp library invokes this method, the two exceptions are propagated to the Reactor pipeline (e.g., via Sink.emitError) for downstream to take appropriate action. 

A specific exception handled inside this method (i.e., an exception won't leave this method) is `ClosedChannelException` (CCE). CCE indicates that the thread executing the invoke method got interrupted, and as a result, JVM closes the message pump pipe. Therefore any resources that rely on the single-threaded ProtonJ message pump (attached to this pipe) are unusable. When this happens, a shutdown signal is emitted via `Sink.One` (which is by design can be completed once) on which the `ReactorConnection` object listen.

#### Findings related to signaling in ReactorDispatcher::invoke (the issues)

In rare cases, MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads can concurrently bypass the guard check (which otherwise would have thrown `RejectedExecutionException` or `IOException`) and enter invoke method, then all those threads run into CCE. (Any threads coming in the future will get `IOException` since the pipe is closed.)

In the case of MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads, two things can happen -.

1. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal to `Sink.One` "concurrently", which violates Reactor Spec. Rule 1.3. 
2. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal  to `Sink.One` "serially"; by design, the Reactor library ignores the second or later emissions.

When `#1` happens, in some cases, we have seen it is going to Reactor global `onErrorDropped` hook, which becomes simply a log entry. Here is such an example log https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24762. The exact reason for going into global-hook needs to be identified, but the point is, we must not violate the spec 1.3.

When `#2` happens, it is as if those additional signals are lost; the `ReactorConnection` care only about the first Shutdown signal, there are no consumption of any future emitted values.

### Proposal:

The fix should make sure -
1. `invoke` do not violate spec 1.3,
2. the signal emission happens only once,
 3. to treat "interrupted" threads (those lost the battle of emission) just like any future threads receiving `RejectedExecutionException` under pipe close. Ideally, the downstream (callers of `invoke`) get to handle the side effect rather than waiting forever for a signal.

If there is a race in `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` that results in concurrent throwing of `ClosedChannelException`, then reactive spec 1.3 may get violated and parts of SDK may not be able to recover. The PR fixes this.

### Long version:

The `ReactorDispatcher::signalWorkQueue` is a private method that the public  API (scoped to implementation) `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` uses. Different parts of the Amqp library uses `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` API from multiple threads to schedule works (that touches ProtonJ thread-unsafe objects) to single-threaded ProtonJ message pump.

The data structure (ConcurrentLinkedQueue) used inside the `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` method is thread-safe and the pipe API for message pump pipe notification is concurrent safe as well. Given `ReactorDispatcher::invoke` belongs to the hot path, these concurrent safeties help avoid marking the method `synchronized`.

The two expected exceptions from the guarding section of this method are - `RejectedExecutionException` REE (related to concurrency) and `IOException` IOE (if message pump pipe is closed). In places where the Amqp library invokes this method, the two exceptions are propagated to the Reactor pipeline (e.g., via Sink.emitError) for downstream to take appropriate action. 

A specific exception handled inside this method (i.e., an exception won't leave this method) is `ClosedChannelException` (CCE). CCE indicates that the thread executing the invoke method got interrupted, and as a result, JVM closes the message pump pipe. Therefore any resources that rely on the single-threaded ProtonJ message pump (attached to this pipe) are unusable. When this happens, a shutdown signal is emitted via `Sink.One` (which is by design can be completed once) on which the `ReactorConnection` object listen.

In rare cases, MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads can concurrently bypass the guard check (which otherwise would have thrown `RejectedExecutionException` or `IOException`) and enter invoke method, then all those threads run into CCE. (Any threads coming in the future will get `IOException` since the pipe is closed.)

In the case of MULTIPLE "interrupted" threads, two things can happen -.

1. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal to `Sink.One` "concurrently", which violates Reactor Spec. Rule 1.3. 
2. More than one of those "interrupted" threads can attempt to send shutdown signal  to `Sink.One` "serially"; by design, the Reactor library ignores the second or later emissions.

When `#1` happens, in some cases, we have seen it is going to Reactor global `onErrorDropped` hook, which becomes simply a log entry. Here is such an example log https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/24762. The exact reason for going into global-hook needs to be identified, but the point is, we must not violate the spec 1.3.

When `#2` happens, it is as if those additional signals are lost; the `ReactorConnection` care only about the first Shutdown signal, there are no consumption of any future emitted values.

### The fix:

The fix should make sure -
1. `invoke` do not violate spec 1.3,
2. the signal emission happens only once,
 3. to treat "interrupted" threads (those lost the battle of emission) just like any future threads receiving `RejectedExecutionException` under pipe close. Ideally, the downstream (callers of `invoke`) get to handle the side effect rather than waiting forever for a signal.

**To Reproduce**
1. Receive a message from a topic using ServiceBusReceiverClient.
2. Then process the received message. Suppose, it takes a very long time, e.g. 2-3 hours.
3. During the processing time, keep renewing the message lock. Please note that the server message lock time for the topic is maximum 5 minutes. And we are renewing the lock every one minute making sure that it never loses the lock.
4. Once the processing is over, send a new message to the same topic using ServiceBusSenderClient.
5. Exception comes: Cannot send a message when request response channel is disposed

**Expected behavior**

Message should have been sent to topic by using ServiceBusSenderClient without any exception. Even if there is some diconnect between sender and server, SDK should revive the connection automatically. Please note that this error is an intermittent error.

**Setup (please complete the following information):**
 - OS: UNIX
 - IDE: IntelliJ
 - Library/Libraries: com.azure:azure-messaging-servicebus:7.5.1
 - Java version: 8
 - App Server/Environment: Tomcat
 - Frameworks: Spring

**Additional context**
1. Error comes while sending a message after a long processing time.
2. Please note that this error is an intermittent error.
3. Earlier this error was very frequent in our UAT environment. Then as per the suggestion from Microsoft support, we upgraded to the latest SDK azure-messaging-servicebus v7.5.1 and it was fixed for us in UAT environment.
4. * Ensuring code consistency

- Based on the implementation thoughts from Connie on this pr https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/26894
- Releasing the messages immediately if there is no active downstream, which reduces the chances of serving expired messages, see #26632 

## What is not in the scope of this pr
- There might be corner cases where we benefit from doing the release (such as when the client closes/terminates), but those are not in the scope of this pr. This pr explicitly targets the case when there is no active downstream.

Description

- Based on the implementation thoughts from Connie on this pr https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/26894
- Releasing the messages immediately if there is no active downstream.
- Reduces the chances of serving expired messages, see #26632 

## What is not in the scope of this pr
- There might be corner cases where we benefit from doing the release (such as when the client closes/terminates), but those are not in the scope of this pr. This pr explicitly targets the case when there is no active downstream.

Description

- Based on the implementation thoughts from Connie on this pr https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/26894
- Releasing the messages immediately if there is no active downstream.
- Reduces the chances of serving expired messages, see #26632 

## What is not in the scope of this pr
- There might be corner cases where we benefit from doing the release (such as when the client closes/terminates), but those are not in the scope of this pr. This pr explicitly targets the case when there is no active downstream.

Description

- Based on the implementation thoughts from Connie on this pr https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/pull/26894
- Releasing the messages immediately if there is no active downstream.
- Reduces the chances of serving expired messages, see #26632 

## What is not in the scope of this pr
- There might be corner cases where we benefit from doing the release (such as when the client closes/terminates), but those are not in the scope of this pr. This pr explicitly targets the case when there is no active downstream.

**To Reproduce**
1. Receive a message from a topic using ServiceBusReceiverClient.
2. Then process the received message. Suppose, it takes a very long time, e.g. 2-3 hours.
3. During the processing time, keep renewing the message lock. Please note that the server message lock time for the topic is maximum 5 minutes. And we are renewing the lock every one minute making sure that it never loses the lock.
4. Once the processing is over, send a new message to the same topic using ServiceBusSenderClient.
5. Exception comes: Cannot send a message when request response channel is disposed

**Expected behavior**

Message should have been sent to topic by using ServiceBusSenderClient without any exception. Even if there is some diconnect between sender and server, SDK should revive the connection automatically. Please note that this error is an intermittent error.

**Setup (please complete the following information):**
 - OS: UNIX
 - IDE: IntelliJ
 - Library/Libraries: com.azure:azure-messaging-servicebus:7.5.1
 - Java version: 8
 - App Server/Environment: Tomcat
 - Frameworks: Spring

**Additional context**
1. Error comes while sending a message after a long processing time.
2. Please note that this error is an intermittent error.
3. Earlier this error was very frequent in our UAT environment. Then as per the suggestion from Microsoft support, we upgraded to the latest SDK azure-messaging-servicebus v7.5.1 and it was fixed for us in UAT environment.
4. **To Reproduce**
1. Receive a message from a topic using ServiceBusReceiverClient.
2. Then process the received message. Suppose, it takes a very long time, e.g. 2-3 hours.
3. During the processing time, keep renewing the message lock. Please note that the server message lock time for the topic is maximum 5 minutes. And we are renewing the lock every one minute making sure that it never loses the lock.
4. Once the processing is over, send a new message to the same topic using ServiceBusSenderClient.
5. Exception comes: Cannot send a message when request response channel is disposed

**Expected behavior**

Message should have been sent to topic by using ServiceBusSenderClient without any exception. Even if there is some diconnect between sender and server, SDK should revive the connection automatically. Please note that this error is an intermittent error.

**Setup (please complete the following information):**
 - OS: UNIX
 - IDE: IntelliJ
 - Library/Libraries: com.azure:azure-messaging-servicebus:7.5.1
 - Java version: 8
 - App Server/Environment: Tomcat
 - Frameworks: Spring

**Additional context**
1. Error comes while sending a message after a long processing time.
2. Please note that this error is an intermittent error.
3. Earlier this error was very frequent in our UAT environment. Then as per the suggestion from Microsoft support, we upgraded to the latest SDK azure-messaging-servicebus v7.5.1 and it was fixed for us in UAT environment.
4. 1. Regarding the intermittent error - It's hard to comment on the possible reason without understanding what happened on the wire; the SDK DEBUG logs covering the error duration (+/- 20 minutes after experiencing the issue) may provide some insights. My only suspicion is SDK exhausted the connection recovery attempts and sender  bumped up the exception to the application.
2. Regarding "ServiceBusReceiverClient was unnecessary pulling the message even when the connection was closed." - the client will try to recover underneath if the amqp connection gets closed (e.g., transient); I think, in such case, any pending credit (for messages) will be placed on the new connection. (I’ll double check and confirm).
3. Regarding the health-check - please subscribe to this issue to get updates: [[Service Bus] Detect connection status · Issue #8561 · Azure/azure-sdk-for-net (github.com)](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/issues/8561) [Though it's .NET repo, the idea is the language agonistic].

Btw, regarding the ~2 hours of auto-renewal, note that if the current connection to the service fails, the lock renewals for messages received on that connection will fail.', 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Azure/azure-sdk-for-java/issues/comments/1029071060/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/alzimmermsft/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}, 'body': "# Description

This PR aims to reduce the number of instances the SDKs buffer memory or optimize the cases where buffering is required.

**Current Changes**

- New method `writeByteBufferToStream` added to `CoreUtils`. Contains optimizations on accessing or writing the contents of the `ByteBuffer` into an `OutputStream`.
- `FluxUtil.toFluxByteBuffer` added an optimization when the `InputStream` is a `FileInputStream`. The `FileChannel` backing the `FileInputStream` is used to get `MappedByteBuffer`s which defers loading the file's contents into memory until it's used.

Thanks, @OlegDokuka. As part of validations, I'm trying to understand the various backpressure involved, IIUC, considering the following code, there are two categories of backpressure - 

```java
Flux<Event> source = ..
Flux<Flux<Event>> sourceWindowed = source.windowTimeout(500, Duration.ofSeconds(3), ..);
```

1. Backpressure to `source` for events.
2. Backpressure to `sourceWindowed` for windows.

If we chain an operator with `prefetch` buffer (e.g., size 50) to `sourceWindowed` - does that mean 

1. It results in requesting 50 "windows" to `sourceWindowed` 
2. which internally requests 50 * 500 "events" to the `source` 
3. with the timeout constrain of 3 sec applied to each of the 50 windows

Is this understanding correct?

4. Is there a setting that caps the number of concurrent "windows" in the above case?
